            "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20\">16. A mother brings her 18-month-old daughter to the emergency department 20 minutes after the child had an episode of choking and gasping while eating potato chips. The mother doesn't think the child went blue during the episode, and the child returned to playing with her toys shortly after the episode. On examination, the child has an intermittent cough but is otherwise playful and in no apparent acute distress. Physical examination is normal, except for an expiratory wheeze noted in the right lung fields. Her respiratory rate is 27/min, pulse rate is 107/min, blood pressure is 95/58 mm Hg, and O2 saturation is 97%. A chest radiograph is obtained and appears normal, but expiratory films are unable to be performed. What is the next step in management?</p>"
